{"focus":{"id":"346e2c8c-686e-5422-a960-f6716141f31c","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1965f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.MD.C.5.b","description":"Apply the formulas $V = l \\times w \\times h$ and $V = b \\times h$ for rectangular prisms to find volumes of right rectangular prisms with whole-number edge lengths in the context of solving real world and mathematical problems.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"MD","cluster":"5.MD.C","level":"substandard"},"ancestors":[{"id":"2736f26a-1e5c-5b90-be28-5f4c801bfd82","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba030d6-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.B.6","description":"Compose simple shapes to form larger shapes. *For example, \"Can you join these two triangles with full sides touching to make a rectangle?\"*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"472fb1eb-7c0d-5904-b9a3-e5a6d94b4ab3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c9896-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.A.1","description":"Describe objects in the environment using names of shapes, and describe the relative positions of these objects using terms such as above, below, beside, in front of, behind, and next to.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"308440b4-e522-5061-85a6-4a5a0a3dce51","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9dcb8a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.A.2","description":"Correctly name shapes regardless of their orientations or overall size.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"d4594d7e-edbd-5c0b-a233-35cccdbbcecf","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e8f43-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.G.A.3","description":"Identify shapes as two-dimensional (lying in a plane, \"flat\") or three-dimensional (\"solid\").","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"G","cluster":"K.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"96c55133-2681-59f9-93af-d27881cbf101","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9dce41-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.MD.A.2","description":"Directly compare two objects with a measurable attribute in common, to see which object has \"more of\"/\"less of\" the attribute, and describe the difference. *For example, directly compare the heights of two children and describe one child as taller/shorter.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"MD","cluster":"K.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"fb8a2e0d-695f-556f-be81-53427c5011dc","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c9af3-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"K.MD.A.1","description":"Describe measurable attributes of objects, such as length or weight. Describe several measurable attributes of a single object.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["K"],"grade":"K","domain":"MD","cluster":"K.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"226b21e4-6dd2-53ce-bd17-68b5c61d3093","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d1dd5-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.G.A.2","description":"Compose two-dimensional shapes (rectangles, squares, trapezoids, triangles, half-circles, and quarter-circles) or three-dimensional shapes (cubes, right rectangular prisms, right circular cones, and right circular cylinders) to create a composite shape, and compose new shapes from the composite shape.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"G","cluster":"1.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"1208a51d-bbaa-5d92-8192-758a71391c59","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba03a8f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.OA.D.7","description":"Understand the meaning of the equal sign, and determine if equations involving addition and subtraction are true or false. *For example, which of the following equations are true and which are false? 6 = 6, 7 = 8 - 1, 5 + 2 = 2 + 5, 4 + 1 = 5 + 2.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"OA","cluster":"1.OA.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"5202eb12-da14-59b3-aaca-d84bfb21b73d","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d205c-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.MD.A.2","description":"Express the length of an object as a whole number of length units, by laying multiple copies of a shorter object (the length unit) end to end; understand that the length measurement of an object is the number of same-size length units that span it with no gaps or overlaps.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"MD","cluster":"1.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"a5c72e23-4039-51b9-8ab3-86f4708d7381","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9bd85b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"1.MD.A.1","description":"Order three objects by length; compare the lengths of two objects indirectly by using a third object.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["1"],"grade":"1","domain":"MD","cluster":"1.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"75f88ede-4b74-51ba-b1e5-2e2d8bd759a6","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e188a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.OA.C.3","description":"Determine whether a group of objects (up to 20) has an odd or even number of members, e.g., by pairing objects or counting them by 2s; write an equation to express an even number as a sum of two equal addends.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"OA","cluster":"2.OA.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"5364ad93-e6c0-51b2-8e09-9466691c324a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ec21d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.OA.C.4","description":"Use addition to find the total number of objects arranged in rectangular arrays with up to 5 rows and up to 5 columns; write an equation to express the total as a sum of equal addends.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"OA","cluster":"2.OA.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"1e7b8f46-92a9-5817-ba90-cf67a66bc81a","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9be543-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.MD.A.1","description":"Measure the length of an object by selecting and using appropriate tools such as rulers, yardsticks, meter sticks, and measuring tapes.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"MD","cluster":"2.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"73138360-d2c3-53b0-aa36-91b9ea38f0f8","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d290b-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"2.G.A.2","description":"Partition a rectangle into rows and columns of same-size squares and count to find the total number of them.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["2"],"grade":"2","domain":"G","cluster":"2.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"2e901b04-79c4-5d68-9077-47e55816f1f4","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f5d5a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.OA.B.5","description":"Apply properties of operations as strategies to multiply and divide.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"OA","cluster":"3.OA.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"affc10f3-aae4-58ea-bc33-ed9fae9be609","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9bfb73-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.OA.A.1","description":"Interpret products of whole numbers, e.g., interpret $5 \\times 7$ as the total number of objects in 5 groups of 7 objects each. *For example, describe a context in which a total number of objects can be expressed as $5 \\div 7$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"OA","cluster":"3.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"64cb2ac3-6f8d-55f5-bbae-6e4de98768e3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d430d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.OA.A.2","description":"Interpret whole-number quotients of whole numbers, e.g., interpret $56 \\div 8$ as the number of objects in each share when 56 objects are partitioned equally into 8 shares, or as a number of shares when 56 objects are partitioned into equal shares of 8 objects each. *For example, describe a context in which a number of shares or a number of groups can be expressed as $56 \\div 8$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"OA","cluster":"3.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"35ca96cb-de02-567b-99f7-dd938c89fb0d","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ec6c0-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.OA.A.4","description":"Determine the unknown whole number in a multiplication or division equation relating three whole numbers. *For example, determine the unknown number that makes the equation true in each of the equations $8 \\times ? = 48$, $5 = \\Box \\div 3$, $6 \\times 6 = ?$.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"OA","cluster":"3.OA.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"813f4e23-c302-532a-845f-cb693fe12b35","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba1826d-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.MD.C.7.b","description":"Multiply side lengths to find areas of rectangles with whole-number side lengths in the context of solving real world and mathematical problems, and represent whole-number products as rectangular areas in mathematical reasoning.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"MD","cluster":"3.MD.C","level":"substandard"},{"id":"b6ea7b48-aac1-55c4-91f8-c5c13ae946d3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0a209-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.MD.D.8","description":"Solve real world and mathematical problems involving perimeters of polygons, including finding the perimeter given the side lengths, finding an unknown side length, and exhibiting rectangles with the same perimeter and different areas or with the same area and different perimeters.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"MD","cluster":"3.MD.D","level":"standard"},{"id":"aad309a8-f04d-5e11-b9b4-7bbe36d72205","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f5a86-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.MD.C.5","description":"Recognize area as an attribute of plane figures and understand concepts of area measurement.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"MD","cluster":"3.MD.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"3dbbcda5-5868-5b18-a07e-5e8b4eb24e58","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba108fe-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.MD.C.7.a","description":"Find the area of a rectangle with whole-number side lengths by tiling it, and show that the area is the same as would be found by multiplying the side lengths.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"MD","cluster":"3.MD.C","level":"substandard"},{"id":"fc25c5ec-af04-54ae-a25e-8e2be4885082","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9fddc7-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"3.MD.C.6","description":"Measure areas by counting unit squares (square cm, square m, square in, square ft, and improvised units).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["3"],"grade":"3","domain":"MD","cluster":"3.MD.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"1b9cdeb7-7c76-55d4-ae26-2a843a886722","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e283e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"4.MD.A.3","description":"Apply the area and perimeter formulas for rectangles in real world and mathematical problems. *For example, find the width of a rectangular room given the area of the flooring and the length, by viewing the area formula as a multiplication equation with an unknown factor.*","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["4"],"grade":"4","domain":"MD","cluster":"4.MD.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"399a1f18-5a00-521e-8af4-f2f569ec505c","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba11b29-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.MD.C.5.a","description":"Find the volume of a right rectangular prism with whole-number side lengths by packing it with unit cubes, and show that the volume is the same as would be found by multiplying the edge lengths, equivalently by multiplying the height by the area of the base. Represent threefold whole-number products as volumes, e.g., to represent the associative property of multiplication.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"MD","cluster":"5.MD.C","level":"substandard"},{"id":"f305010a-cdfe-57e6-adf0-7eff49eb921c","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e32dc-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.MD.C.3","description":"Recognize volume as an attribute of solid figures and understand concepts of volume measurement.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"MD","cluster":"5.MD.C","level":"standard"},{"id":"5bc00d79-63fc-552a-bb76-ada451c72768","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ed5fc-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.MD.C.4","description":"Measure volumes by counting unit cubes, using cubic cm, cubic in, cubic ft, and improvised units.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"MD","cluster":"5.MD.C","level":"standard"}],"descendants":[{"id":"c41aafda-f8ce-589f-87de-d172c97b4667","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba20ee1-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"5.MD.C.5.c","description":"Recognize volume as additive. Find volumes of solid figures composed of two non-overlapping right rectangular prisms by adding the volumes of the non-overlapping parts, applying this technique to solve real world problems.","statementType":"Component","gradeLevels":["5"],"grade":"5","domain":"MD","cluster":"5.MD.C","level":"substandard"},{"id":"a6b910c8-ac87-51b3-af40-a6372cb1e970","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9d6553-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"6.G.A.2","description":"Find the volume of a right rectangular prism with fractional edge lengths by packing it with unit cubes of the appropriate unit fraction edge lengths, and show that the volume is the same as would be found by multiplying the edge lengths of the prism. Apply the formulas $V = l w h$ and $V = b h$ to find volumes of right rectangular prisms with fractional edge lengths in the context of solving real-world and mathematical problems.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["6"],"grade":"6","domain":"G","cluster":"6.G.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"04ae82c5-8a43-52b8-b2f7-9353d5b82bdc","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9ff914-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"7.G.B.6","description":"Solve real-world and mathematical problems involving area, volume and surface area of two- and three-dimensional objects composed of triangles, quadrilaterals, polygons, cubes, and right prisms.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["7"],"grade":"7","domain":"G","cluster":"7.G.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"52aff65f-f9bf-51bb-99c0-0a53063975ae","caseIdentifierUUID":"6ba0026f-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"8.G.B.6","description":"Explain a proof of the Pythagorean Theorem and its converse.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["8"],"grade":"8","domain":"G","cluster":"8.G.B","level":"standard"},{"id":"ef4ff21d-897e-598d-b731-2d5b8a2b31c3","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9c77f2-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-MG.A.1","description":"Use geometric shapes, their measures, and their properties to describe objects (e.g., modeling a tree trunk or a human torso as a cylinder).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-MG","cluster":"HSG-MG.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"636789d4-4a59-5e0e-91cd-902823701dd5","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9e763a-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-MG.A.3","description":"Apply geometric methods to solve design problems (e.g., designing an object or structure to satisfy physical constraints or minimize cost; working with typographic grid systems based on ratios).","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-MG","cluster":"HSG-MG.A","level":"standard"},{"id":"ec224230-3b80-5156-b6b2-82b68e282880","caseIdentifierUUID":"6b9f195e-d7cc-11e8-824f-0242ac160002","code":"HSG-SRT.B.4","description":"Prove theorems about triangles.","statementType":"Standard","gradeLevels":["9","10","11","12"],"grade":"HS","domain":"G-SRT","cluster":"HSG-SRT.B","level":"standard"}],"edges":[{"id":"8abc2bee-39ed-51f2-b7a2-1d32992374bb","label":"buildsTowards","source":"fb8a2e0d-695f-556f-be81-53427c5011dc","target":"96c55133-2681-59f9-93af-d27881cbf101"},{"id":"4ac6fd4c-8b0f-56a7-b865-2e3bdde6870f","label":"buildsTowards","source":"96c55133-2681-59f9-93af-d27881cbf101","target":"a5c72e23-4039-51b9-8ab3-86f4708d7381"},{"id":"fce492a4-3d4f-526a-bb35-d16e870ab11c","label":"buildsTowards","source":"472fb1eb-7c0d-5904-b9a3-e5a6d94b4ab3","target":